Let's avoid using `CompletableFuture` combinators such as `thenAccept` since it's easy to use the default executor instead of the implicit `ExecutionContext` that we have in scope. 
```suggestion
for {
  newMainClasses <- connection.mainClasses(new b.ScalaMainClassesParams(targetsList)).asScala
  newTestClasses <- connection.testClasses(new b.ScalaTestClassesParams(targetsList))
} yield {
  cacheMainClasses(newMainClasses)
  cacheTestClasses(newTestClasses)
}
```

Nit: for consistency with the rest of the codebase
```suggestion
    } {
      classesOf(target).testSuites.put(objectSymbol, className)
    }
```

Could this be simplified to:
```scala
def findTestClassByName(name: String) = findClassByName(name, _.testClasses.values.find(_ == name))
def findMainClassByName(name: String) = findClassByName(name, _.mainClasses.values.find(_.getClassName() == name))
def findClassByName(name: String, f: Classes => Seq[Any]) = {
  index
      .mapValues(f)
      .toList
      .collect {
        case (target, Some(clazz)) => clazz -> target
      }
}
```
